1ï¸âƒ£ Introduction to Docker Networking

Docker networking enables containers to communicate with:

    Other containers
    
    The Docker host
    
    External systems (internet)

Each container runs in an isolated network namespace and Docker provides virtual networks to connect them.

2ï¸âƒ£ Core Docker Networking Concepts
ğŸ”¹ Container Networking

    Each container gets:
    
        Its own IP address
        
        Its own network stack
    
    Containers are isolated by default

ğŸ”¹ Network

    A virtual switch
    
    Containers connected to the same network can communicate
    
    Communication happens via container name (DNS)

ğŸ”¹ Port Mapping

    Maps a containerâ€™s internal port to the host machine.
    
    docker run -p 8080:80 nginx
    
    Host Port 8080 â†’ Container Port 80

3ï¸âƒ£ Types of Docker Networks

Docker provides 5 main network drivers.

1. Bridge Network (Default)
    Most commonly used
    Containers get private IPs
    Containers can talk to each other
    Uses NAT to communicate with host
    docker network create my-bridge
    docker run --network my-bridge nginx
      
    Use cases
      Microservices
      Web applications
      Local development

2. Host Network

    Container shares hostâ€™s network
    No isolation
    Faster performance
    docker run --network host nginx


Pros
    No port mapping required

Cons
    Port conflicts
    Less secure

3. None Network
    No networking at all
    Completely isolated container   
    docker run --network none alpine


Use cases
    Security testing   
    Offline batch jobs

4. Overlay Network (Swarm)
    Used for multi-host communication
    Requires Docker Swarm

docker network create -d overlay my-overlay

Use cases:
    Distributed systems  
    Clustered applications
