docker network rm my-network

5ï¸âƒ£ EXPOSE vs -p (Port Publishing)
ğŸ”¹ EXPOSE

Dockerfile instruction

Documents which port the container listens on

Does NOT open the port

EXPOSE 8080


âœ” Internal container communication
âŒ No external access

ğŸ”¹ -p or --publish

Runtime option

Maps container port to host port

Allows external access

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx


âœ” External access
âœ” Host â†’ Container traffic

ğŸ”¥ Difference Summary
Feature	EXPOSE	-p
Where used	Dockerfile	docker run
Opens port externally	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Documentation	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
Required	âŒ No	âŒ No
Interview Answer

EXPOSE documents container ports, while -p publishes and maps them to the host.

6ï¸âƒ£ Multiple Dockerfiles in One Folder
Folder Structure
project/
â”œâ”€â”€ Dockerfile.app1
â”œâ”€â”€ Dockerfile.app2

Build Images
docker build -f Dockerfile.app1 -t app1-image .
docker build -f Dockerfile.app2 -t app2-image .

Run Containers
docker run -d --name app1 app1-image
docker run -d --name app2 app2-image

7ï¸âƒ£ Meaning of -f and -t
ğŸ”¹ -f (File)

Specifies which Dockerfile to use

docker build -f Dockerfile.custom .

ğŸ”¹ -t (Tag)

Assigns name and version to the image

docker build -t my-app:1.0 .

8ï¸âƒ£ Docker Commands Cheat Sheet (Beginner â†’ Advanced)
